explanation:
For determining compliance with the MISRA rule "A function parameter should not be modified":
- UT_EntryKey_t (typedef): Needed to know whether FuncKey is an integer/scalar or a pointer type. If it is a pointer type the analysis must check whether the pointer itself is written to inside the function (forbidden) versus the pointee being modified (allowed).
- UT_EntryType_t (typedef): Same reason for TestMode — must know if this parameter is a scalar or a pointer so we can detect any modification of the parameter object itself.
- UT_ENTRYTYPE_UNUSED (macro/enum): The code compares TestMode to this constant; its type (enum/integer) confirms the kind of comparison and helps ensure no macro expansion hides writes to the parameter.
- UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS (macro): Appears in the modulo and bounds checks. Its definition (macro value/type) is needed to ensure no macro side effects could rewrite FuncKey or TestMode and to reason about index arithmetic (but not itself a parameter modification, so included to rule out hidden modifications).
- UT_MaxStubSearchLen (global variable): Read and possibly written in the function. Its declaration/type is required to check there is no aliasing that could cause a write to this global to actually modify one of the parameters (e.g., via overlapping storage in exotic implementations).
- UT_StubTableEntry_t (struct): The function reads fields EntryType and FuncKey from the table entries. Knowing the member types (and whether any are pointers or have overloaded macros) is necessary to ensure those member accesses do not alias or modify the function parameters.
- UT_StubTable (array): The object indexed (&UT_StubTable[Idx]) is used inside the loop. Its declaration and linkage/type help rule out any unexpected aliasing or macro expansion that could modify the parameters.

These symbols provide the type/definition context needed to prove whether FuncKey or TestMode are ever assigned to or otherwise modified inside UT_GetStubEntry (including ruling out hidden modifications via macro expansions or aliasing).
